{"title":"How to watch the Tour of Britain Women 2025","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/watch-tour-of-britain-women","date":1748961345000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/watch-tour-of-britain-women\">How to watch the Tour of Britain Women 2025</a></p>\n\n<p>The Tour of Britain Women, the only WorldTour race in the UK, returns from Thursday 5th June to Sunday 8th June in England and Scotland. While it is the second edition under the Tour of Britain Women name and British Cycling organisation, this is technically the ten-year anniversary of the event previously called the Women’s Tour.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>For 2025 the race begins in Yorkshire and a short Stage 1 ends in Redcar. Stage 2 departs Hartlepool and could be a potentially GC-decisive day that ends on the steep Saltburn Bank climb. It’s then a trip across the border for Stage 3 around Kelso before the last day culminating on a circuit in Glasgow.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n<p>Last year Lotte Kopecky topped the general classification after winning the first two stages. Great Britain’s Anna Henderson finished second, 17sec down with Kopecky’s SD Worx-Protime teammate Christine Majerus in third.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Kopecky and Majerus will not be on the start line this year, but their team brings the world’s best sprinter Lorena Wiebes to go hunting for stage wins. Henderson is back though, this time with a strong Lidl-Trek squad. Other GC favourites include Liège-Bastogne-Liège winner Kim Le Court-Pienaar, Olympic champion Kristen Faulkner and Canyon-SRAM-Zondacrypto’s Cecilie Uttrup Ludwig. Keep an eye on Sarah Van Dam from the Ceratizit team too, the Canadian is having a run of fine form, barely finishing outside the top five since mid-April and riding to third overall at Itzulia.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/newsletters\"><img width=\"970\" height=\"332\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-970x332.webp\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-970x332.webp 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-300x103.webp 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-768x263.webp 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-1536x526.webp 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-2048x701.webp 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-750x257.webp 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2025/05/Newsletter-flash-v2-1-1140x390.webp 1140w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>Where and how to watch the Tour of Britain Women 2025</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-970x647.webp\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-970x646.webp 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-300x200.webp 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-768x512.webp 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-1536x1024.webp 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-2048x1365.webp 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-750x500.webp 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-1140x760.webp 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-465x310.webp 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-620x413.webp 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/05/GettyImages-2156780689-350x233.webp 350w\" /><figcaption>Matt McNulty/Getty Images</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In the UK, the Tour of Britain Women 2025 will be broadcast live for free on the BBC. Viewers can catch the action on BBC iPlayer, the BBC Sport website and app and on the BBC Red Button channel. The race will also be broadcast online through Discovery+. Highlights will be shown on TNT channels.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>If the race isn’t being broadcast in your country or you are travelling abroad, a VPN will allow you to hide your device’s location to access content that is normally geo-blocked. One such VPN provider is <a href=\"https://go.expressvpn.com/m5yJGZ\" target=\"_blank\">ExpressVPN</a>, which is <a href=\"https://www.techradar.com/reviews/expressvpn\" target=\"_blank\">well reviewed</a>, helps users to find free to watch cycling, and costs start from around £5 per month.</p>\n\n\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Read more: <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/how-to-watch-cycling-for-less-in-the-uk\">How to watch cycling for less in the UK</a></strong></li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Read more:</strong> <strong><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/free-to-air-cycling\">Which countries can watch cycling for free in 2025?</a></strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk